  "nlp_and_classifier_notes": {
    "bengali_nlp_tooling_maturity": "Moderate and growing. BanglaBERT (BUET NLP group, 2021/2022) is the de facto foundation model for Bengali NLP, demonstrating state-of-the-art performance on NLU benchmarks including hate speech, sentiment, fake news, and named entity recognition. Source: Emergent Mind BanglaBERT overview — [|https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/banglabert|]. BanglaBERT achieves F1 ~0.89 on Bangla social media toxicity group detection tasks (Springer ICITA 2024 — [|https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-981-96-1758-6_46|]). However, BanglaBERT is trained primarily on standard Unicode Bengali; performance on degraded Banglish (Roman-script) is substantially lower. A dedicated BanglaHateBERT model for abusive language detection in Bengali also exists. Key limitation: none of these models cover clinical-domain toxicity or the specific Bangladeshi religious/caste slur ontology needed for this deployment.",
    "banglish_nlp_tooling_maturity": "Sparse but now exists. BanTH (NAACL 2025 Findings) is the first multi-label transliterated Bangla (Banglish/Roman-script) hate speech dataset, comprising 37,350 YouTube comments with 7 hate categories: Political, Religious, Gender, Personal Offense, Abusive/Violence, Origin, and Body Shaming. It establishes transformer-based baselines including further pre-trained 'Transliterated Bangla Encoders' (TB-Encoders). Best model achieves ~F1 0.78 on multi-label task. Source: arXiv 2410.13281 / NAACL 2025 — [|https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.13281|]; GitHub — [|https://github.com/farhanishmam/BanTH|]. A smaller prior resource (Sazzed 2021) covered ~3K transliterated Bangla-English abusive comments. BengaliHateCB (Saha et al. 2024) is a hybrid model trained on both Bengali and Banglish datasets. The BanTH dataset is sourced from YouTube (not Facebook/clinical contexts), covers religion and gender categories but not caste, colorism, or superstition-based harm.",
    "known_toxicity_datasets_bengali": "Multiple datasets exist for Unicode Bengali:\n1. Bengali Hate Speech Dataset (Karim et al. 2020/UCI): ~30,000 examples from Facebook/social media, categorised as political, personal, geopolitical, religious, gender-abusive. Covers Bangladesh and India sources. Source: UCI ML Repo — [|https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/719/bengali+hate+speech+detection+dataset|]; GitHub — [|https://github.com/rezacsedu/Bengali-Hate-Speech-Dataset|].\n2. BD-SHS (Romim et al. LREC 2022): >50,200 offensive comments from Bangladeshi social networking sites, hierarchical annotation. Source: ACL Anthology — [|https://aclanthology.org/2022.lrec-1.552/|].\n3. ToxLex_bn (PMC 2022): ~1,959 bigram toxic lexical entries from 2.2M Facebook comments (Bangladesh/India users); includes communal, misogynist, sexist categories; ~13% entries feature non-standard/unusual spelling; Romanised Bangla was excluded from this dataset. Source: PMC — [|https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9256543/|].\n4. BLP-2023 and BLP-2025 shared tasks (ACL BanglaLP workshop): Violence-inciting text detection and hate speech tasks in Bangla. Source: ACL Anthology BLP-2023 — [|https://aclanthology.org/2023.banglalp-1.29.pdf|].\nCritical gap: none of these datasets specifically address the Bangladeshi clinical chatbot domain, caste-coded slurs, colorism, or superstition-based harmful health advice. Many mix Bangladesh and West Bengal (India) sources; West Bengali cultural context differs meaningfully from Bangladeshi.",
    "known_toxicity_datasets_banglish": "BanTH (NAACL 2025 Findings) is the first and currently only large-scale multi-label hate speech dataset for transliterated Bangla (Banglish), with 37,350 samples and 7 hate categories. Source: arXiv 2410.13281 — [|https://arxiv.org/abs/2410.13281|]. This directly resolves the previously flagged gap: a Banglish toxicity resource now exists, but it covers YouTube comments (not clinical chat), lacks caste/colorism/superstition categories, and is not fine-grained enough for the clinical deployment's harm ontology without significant extension.",
    "classifier_degraded_text_robustness": "Partially addressed by BanTH and BLP-2025 work. BanTH shows that models struggle with code-switched regional dialects and terms lacking direct English equivalents, leading to misclassification of subtle offensive content. BLP-2025 adversarial training (FGSM + text normalisation) improves BanglaBERT robustness on noisy social-media Bengali text, raising F1 from ~70% to ~72–74% on hate speech detection. Source: arXiv 2511.18324 (BLP-2025 system paper) — [|https://arxiv.org/html/2511.18324|]. However, no evaluation of toxicity classifier robustness under clinical-domain noisy Banglish inputs (phonetically degraded, missing punctuation, code-switched) has been published.",
    "religious_slur_lexicons": "ToxLex_bn includes communal hate terms from Facebook Bengali content (Bangladesh/India users), with ~1,959 bigram toxic entries across 8 thematic classes including communal categories. Source: PMC — [|https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9256543/|]. The Bengali Hate Speech Dataset (Karim et al.) includes 175 abusive terms frequently used in religious and political hate contexts. Source: UCI ML Repo — [|https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/719/bengali+hate+speech+detection+dataset|]. However, no published academic or community lexicon specifically cataloguing Bangladeshi Bengali religious minority slurs (e.g., 'malaun' and analogues) and caste-coded terms as a standalone resource has been identified. These terms appear in the datasets above but are not isolated or documented as a dedicated deployable lexicon.",
